rComments: Andrew is one of the most interesting profs at U of T. As a lecturer, he can sometimes be a little dry, but if you take the time to get to know him, you will like him. If you are lucky enough to get to work on one of his research projects, which consistently get government funding, you will find the experience very rewarding.

Andrew's classes are definitely not bird courses. He teaches for the students that like thinking through how they want to shape the future. He's incredibly supportive of students who are highly engaged in taking action with their careers. More than many professors, he'll help you push your ideas forward. If you have no ideas, you won't like him.

Subjected us to a poorly-designed graduate course which focused on busy work rather than providing a sound foundation in research methods. Appears much more concerned with his research rather then with teaching. Next time I will ask for my money back.

Often seems like he'd rather not be there.  Frequently comes across as arrogant.  When asked questions from class during lecture, often dismissed them, or spent 2 min. not answering ques. in the end. Could not seem to get marking/evaluation criteria straight amongst he and co-lecturer and t.a. Come to lecture prepared with *plenty* of caffeine!
